review_content: [Clash is] portrayed as a mild-mannered, kind, giving, supremely talented soul, with a deep love for the puppet he animates and the children who love him.

While the script has its fair share of treacly moments intended to manipulate viewers into caring deeply for this duo, Billy Crystal's dream project about his beloved Yankees and one of their great chapters gets a heroic treatment in 61*.
It's a cautionary tale but not a preachy one, told with affection and sympathy courtesy of Richard LaGravenese's intelligent, humorous and concise screenplay.

The characters in this Christmas special really make it... Rudolph and Hermey are wonderful examples of lovable misfits. And the wonderful thing about this special is that neither of these characters changes to fit their surroundings.
Not a radical act of film-making and visually, it is far from an inspired piece of work - but it's a great example of a film where the strong content rules supreme.

Ingmar Bergman has never before made a movie so warm, happy and innocent... It's as if all this joy has been building up inside him during the great decade of metaphysical films beginning with Persona.

review_content: Cedric the Entertainer comes close to sharing Gleason's gift for, well, entertaining. He's the biggest reason this version of The Honeymooners is such an amusing surprise.
This film is stunning to look at, with wonderful sets, interesting costumes, and yet another work of gorgeous cinematography by Bergman fave, Sven Nykvist.

review_content: There's no denying that the decaying New York of the late-'70s/early-'80s was a fascinating proving ground for starving artists. And Blank City is great arty eye candy. But you'll appreciate it best if the skinny-tie years were indeed your glory days.
"Kevin comes alive through Elmo," says Clash's mother in the film, and it's true. Watching him manipulate the puppet for adoring children, a kindness and joy shines through.
It's cheerful and ready to have a good time, and it's blessed with some truly unique characters.
Best Worst Movie might not be the best movie ever made about a bad movie. But it's still a pretty good and pretty fun one.
People love Elmo, but it's also pretty clear that "Being Elmo: A Puppeteer's Journey" is a documentary that plays well to a crowd on its own.

movie_title: A Walk Into the Sea: Danny Williams and the Warhol Factory
review_content: First-time director Esther Robinson proves that a dash of subjectivity in documentary isn't always a bad thing, showing a remarkable clarity of vision and thirst for knowledge in her superb 'A Walk Into the Sea: Danny Williams and the Warhol Factory'.
Delicious insider tales of the making of some of your favorite films enrich this wonderfully informative and entertaining doc about casting directors.
It's a joyous production; the music is alive and dynamic, the skits are clever and funny and self-effacing and the show crackles with energy...
A triumph of great entertainment. Whether it is great filmmaking is a matter of taste.
Much more than a biopic about Liberace, this expertly assembled film recounts a true love story in a way we rarely see on-screen: with honest humour, real feeling and startling insight.
The film also provides an inspiring reminder for the young and the rest of us that there is a vital relationship between the best kind of work and passionate play.
Adoring, feel-good, sweet documentary about Kevin Clash, best known as Elmo's hand, voice and soul.
The movie falls into a quickly boring pattern: Ralph does something boneheaded. Ed says something stupid and falls down. Alice becomes exasperated with Ralph. Repeat.
The fictionalised account of Carlos's personal life is intriguing, but the deeper root of his anger remains unclear beyond the rhetoric.

By itself, the golden age of Trumbo's career would make for an inspired documentary. But, alas, history situates him in another story, a tragedy that nearly consumed him and many other members of Hollywood.
The cinematic equivalent of staging a disaster and then bitching about the mess.
The story as told is just too depressing, too empty and, most of all, too dead and gone.
If you think American Idol is a cultural phenomenon here, imagine its impact on a country devastated by 30 years of internal strife, religious intolerance, civil war and foreign invasion.
Carlos was like a terrorist version of James Bond, a high-living, jet-setting playboy terrorist for hire.

Judging by the film's alternately self-pitying, self-aggrandizing, and bitter tone, the schlock director is afflicted with a bizarre lack of self-consciousness to rival Smith's own impregnable wall of self-delusion.

An informative documentary revealing how decades of war and years of Taliban repression have fallen to the wayside, however briefly, as Kabul's answer to American Idol seduces a violence-weary Afghanistan.
John Leguizamo steals the show as its sleazy trainer -- not that there's much to steal from John Schultz's joylessly schematic paycheck.

Olivier Assayas' epic account of the life and myth of real-life terrorist Carlos the Jackal is a mesmerizing portrait of a committed activist who transforms himself into a media-hungry rock star of an international terrorist.
The intriguing movie works in fits and spurts but keeps you with it even with some troubling logical problems.
Fifteen Minutes pretty much recycles the media paranoia and fear found in Mad City with passing stabs at Snuff and Payback. It sinks quickly off the waters of lower Manhattan.
Made-for-TV eyewash for disheartened Bears fans to drown their sorrows in.

The film is both optimistic and depressing. This film is about a real war with real deaths that is going on in Afghanistan and one of the battlefields of that war is a pop music contest on television.
Some movies are just bad. Some are so bad they're good. And others are so intensely bad that they rise to a level of perverse greatness.
Its savage indictment of the nexus involving media, crime and a voracious public is a cinematic statement difficult to ignore.
Two horrifyingly bad hours that should stand as a reminder to keep Hollywood away from big issues or anything else it can put in its mouth and choke on.

Assayas, hopping the globe from bloody episode to bloody episode with little pause for reflection, offers a concise history in how radical political violence played out across Europe during the final Cold War years.
Here's the bottom line: Would people be singing the praises of this film if it was equally well-made but was the story of Mohamed Atta? A terrorist is a terrorist.
